C++ Domain outside embedded systems. 

You can absolutely build a strong career in C++ outside embedded systems. 
In fact, a lot of high-performance and infrastructure-heavy software still depends on C++ because of speed, memory control, and low-level access.

Given your background — 
Qt/QML, modern C++17, models, backend logic, Linux, debugging — you already align better with “systems/application C++” than pure embedded firmware.

Some major C++ domains outside embedded:

* Desktop application development
  Heavy use of Qt. Examples: CAD tools, IDEs, trading terminals, engineering software, medical imaging apps.
  Companies:    [Qt Group](https://www.qt.io?utm_source=chatgpt.com), 
                [Autodesk](https://www.autodesk.com?utm_source=chatgpt.com), 
                [Siemens](https://www.siemens.com?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

* Finance / low-latency systems
  Trading engines, risk systems, market data processing. Very strong C++ demand because latency matters.

* Game engines & graphics
  Engines, rendering pipelines, physics systems.
  Examples: Epic Games with Unreal Engine, graphics middleware, simulation software.

* Browser / database / infrastructure software
  Browsers, databases, compilers, storage engines, distributed systems.
  Examples: Google Chrome, MySQL, parts of LLVM.

* Robotics / simulation / autonomy
  Not necessarily embedded firmware. Often Linux + networking + real-time-ish applications + visualization.

* Cybersecurity & networking
  VPNs, packet processing, protocol stacks, performance tooling.

* Audio/video/media software
  Streaming engines, codecs, video editing, media processing.

* Scientific / engineering software
  Simulation, numerical computing, imaging, instrumentation tools.

For you specifically, these paths fit naturally:

1. Qt/C++ desktop engineer
   You already work with:

* QML
* models/views
* backend integration
* threading
* Linux
* debugging

That stack is valuable in industrial software companies.

2. Systems/backend C++ engineer
   Move deeper into:

* multithreading
* networking
* async systems
* IPC
* performance optimization
* Linux internals

3. Tools/platform engineer
   Developer tools, frameworks, SDKs, middleware, infrastructure libraries.

A practical reality:
Pure “modern C++ application development” jobs are fewer than Java/web jobs, but the engineers are also fewer. Good C++ engineers remain hard to replace.

If your goal is long-term stability plus interesting engineering work, I’d focus on:

* Modern C++17/20
* Linux
* debugging/profiling
* concurrency
* networking
* architecture/design
* Qt only as a UI layer, not your entire identity

That combination opens far more doors than staying narrowly “Qt developer” or “embedded only.”

You do not need to move into embedded to have a serious C++ career.